  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is **illegal** in virtually every country around the world. It is a serious financial crime that involves processing or disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear legitimate. The process typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illicit funds into the financial system.  \n2. **Layering**: Conducting complex transactions to obscure the source of the money.  \n3. **Integration**: Making the \"cleaned\" money appear legitimate by reintroducing it into the economy.  \n\nGovernments and international organizations (like the Financial Action Task Force - FATF) have established strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, asset seizures, and lengthy prison sentences. Additionally, financial institutions and businesses are required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and report suspicious activities. \n\nIf you suspect money laundering or are involved in a situation related to it, it\u2019s important to seek legal advice immediately.",
